  "sections": [
    {
      "name": "Kodama (Tree Kami)",
      "sections": [
        {
          "image": {
            "image": "Sidebar_5_TreasureAndRewards.png",
            "name": "Treasure and Rewards",
            "type": "image"
          },
          "name": "Kami Treasure",
          "sidebar_heading": "Treasure and Rewards",
          "sidebar_type": "treasure_and_rewards",
          "sources": [
            {
              "link": {
                "alt": "Monster Core 2 pg. 205",
                "aonid": 276,
                "game-obj": "Sources",
                "name": "Monster Core 2 pg. 205",
                "type": "link"
              },
              "name": "Monster Core 2",
              "page": 205,
              "type": "source"
            }
          ],
          "subtype": "sidebar",
          "text": "Kami have no use for valuables or other material possessions, but the sites they protect are often rich with natural resources or even sometimes dotted with relics from bygone eras. One of the greatest kami treasures is a kodama\u2019s *spiritual rope*. Although these ropes grant no power to mortals, a freely gifted *spiritual rope* from a kodama is seen as a mark of the utmost purity and worthiness.",
          "type": "section"
        }
      ],
      "sources": [
        {
          "link": {
            "alt": "Monster Core 2 pg. 205",
            "aonid": 276,
            "game-obj": "Sources",
            "name": "Monster Core 2 pg. 205",
            "type": "link"
          },
          "name": "Monster Core 2",
          "page": 205,
          "type": "source"
        }
      ],
      "text": "A kodama is a type of kami who inhabits a tree. Kodama commonly appear in old Tian forests, especially old-growth forests far removed from civilization. In the Forest of Spirits in Minkai, for example, so many trees are possessed by kodama that a traveler might pass by hundreds, if not thousands, of these beings while journeying through a single acre of woodland.   \n  \nKodama try their utmost to protect their sacred trees, but a single kodama is a minor obstacle to most oni or others who have no qualms about desecrating forests or harvesting them for natural resources. Like trees in a forest, kodama are most powerful in great numbers and among other kami, whom they can bolster with their magical straw ropes while distracting strong enemies with their mesmerizing presence. On the other hand, kodama bear no ill will toward those who respect their wards, even allowing druids and other deferential creatures to dwell within their bounds. They might even subtly guide lost travelers out of the forest or back to safety.",
      "type": "section"
    }
  ],
